# Debounce Function in JavaScript
A debounce function delays invoking a function until after a specified wait time has elapsed since the last time it was called.

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait) {
  let timeoutId;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), wait);
  };
}

// Example usage:
const debouncedSearch = debounce((query) => {
  console.log('Searching for:', query);
}, 500);

// Simulating rapid input (would normally be from an input event)
debouncedSearch('A');  // No output yet
debouncedSearch('Ap'); // No output yet
debouncedSearch('App');// Output: "Searching for: App" (after 500ms delay)
debouncedSearch('Appl');// No new output (initial timeout cleared and reset)
```

This is useful for handling rapid-fire events like window resizing, keyboard input, or scroll events efficiently.
